      "commit_id": null,
      "commit_url": null,
      "created_at": "2026-06-01T09:48:59Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-06-01T09:48:59Z",
      "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body": "> Per [BIP327](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0327.mediawiki?plain=1&rgh-link-date=2026-05-30T21%3A16%3A09Z#L98), a `secnonce` consisting of only zero bytes is invalid for Sign and will cause it to fail.\r\n\r\nI think you're confusing different abstraction levels here. `secnonce` in the BIP is a byte array of length 64. `secp256k1_musig_secnonce` is a C type. Blobs of that type need more than 64 bytes in memory. And yes, (purported) blobs of that type having an all-zero memory representation are indeed rejected by `secp256k1_musig_partial_sign` (by crashing). But this is not because they represent a `secnonce` of 64 zero bytes; it is simply because don't even represent a valid `secp256k1_musig_secnonce`. Crashing is just a courtesy of libsecp256k1 -- the library could also just invoke UB.\r\n\r\nBut none of this should matter for code in Bitcoin Core as a caller of libsecp256k1. The only thing you should make sure as a caller is to pass a `secp256k1_musig_secnonce` to `secp256k1_musig_partial_sign` only if `secp256k1_musig_nonce_gen` succeeded on it.",
